title: PfMP Practice Exam 02
description: Comprehensive practice test covering Governance, Stakeholder Engagement, and Life Cycle Management.

questions.text: Mr. Henry is a Portfolio Manager and is working on his portfolio during portfolio construction to create a variety of portfolio scenarios using different combinations of both potential and current components. Which process, tool & technique is Mr. Henry involved in and what is the output?

options.text: Develop Charter, Scenario Analysis, Portfolio Structure
Develop Charter, Capability and Capacity Analysis, Portfolio Structure
Develop Charter, Capability and Capacity Analysis, Portfolio

questions.explanation:
Scenario analysis is an analytical method that enables decision makers to create a variety of portfolio scenarios using different combinations of both potential and current components, evaluating their possible outcomes. The result of this analysis is the portfolio structure (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 4.2.2.1, Pg# 48)

- C&C Analysis is a T&T of Develop Portfolio Charter process, however, it is performed to understand how much work portfolio is able to perform based on the resources available (capacity), as well as the ability to determine the constraints generated by certain skill set limitations, financial, asset capacity factors (capability). It does not determine the portfolio structure
- ‘Portfolio’ is not an output of Develop Portfolio Charter process

questions.text:
You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently defining the metrics to measure the portfolio benefits and value towards the organizational objectives during Portfolio Execution.

Which of the following is covered as part of activities performed during Define Portfolio Performance Management Plan process?

options.text: Portfolio Value and Component Resource Management

questions.explanation:
The Portfolio Performance Management Plan documents how the organization plans to measure, monitor, control and report (1) portfolio performance, (2) resource management, and (3) portfolio value (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Read the introductory para of Section 6.1, Pg# 87)

- The other choice are incorrect. Component performance, resource management and value delivery is performed as part of component management (project & program management), not portfolio management. Portfolio manager uses the performance, resource and value delivery reports from component managers, and aggregate them as part of portfolio reports to present to

questions.text:
As the Portfolio Manager, you have scored the portfolio components and are analyzing the data in order to prioritize the components. Consider that your portfolio would get organizational resources for two components only. Using the following multi-criteria scoring table, which would be the top two components that will be executed in your portfolio?

| Portfolio Components | Component Score |
| :--- | :--- |
| Customer Growth Program - A | 100 |
| Technological Adv Project - B | 387.5 |
| Regulatory Project - C | 341.4 |
| Revenue Generation Project - D | 561.3 |
questions.explanation: As per the Multi-criteria scoring technique, the higher the component score, the higher the priority. However, mandatory criteria, such as regulatory, legal, operations deserve particular attention. Portfolio components that are required to comply with such mandates need to ensure their inclusion in the final portfolio regardless of their scoring and ranking. The other components would be ranked in the portfolio as per the scoring. Accordingly, the two components that would be selected in the given portfolio are component C and D (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 5.2.2.3, Last few lines of Weighted Ranking and Scoring technique, Pg# 70)

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager of VirtualTech portfolio at TGR organization, you have just created an initial list of portfolio components. In which portfolio management process are you working?
questions.explanation:
The 'Portfolio' that is created as a result of 'Develop Portfolio Strategic plan' process is just a high level initial list of components (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 4.1.3.2, Pg# 46)

- The purpose of the 'Define Portfolio' process is to create an up-to-date comprehensive list of qualified portfolio components by identifying, categorizing, scoring, and ranking portfolio components which is eventually executed in the organization
- 'Develop Portfolio Charter' and 'Define Roadmap' processes do not create Portfolio jey deliverable as output

questions.text: Authorizing and Controlling process group consists of all the below activities except:

options.text: Alignment of portfolio components to the organizational strategy
Track and monitor component performance for strategic alignment

questions.explanation:
'Alignment of portfolio components to the organizational strategy' is activity of Aligning process group. Aligning Process Group consists of processes to manage and optimize the portfolio. This process group determines how portfolio components will be categorized, evaluated, selected for inclusion, modification, or elimination in the portfolio. The processes in this process group enable a structured method for aligning the mix of portfolio components to the organization’s strategy (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 3.1.2, Pg# 32)

- The other choices are activities of A&C process group. Authorizing and Controlling process group determines how to monitor strategic changes; tracks and reviews performance indicators for alignment; and authorizes the portfolio components. These authorizing and oversight processes are the active part of the portfolio and are usually an ongoing function of the organization's governing body.

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently defining the key performance metrics to measure the portfolio benefits and value towards the organizational objectives during Portfolio Execution. It is important that portfolio performance metrics are SMART objectives. SMART stands for:
questions.explanation: Portfolio performance measures and targets (metrics) are set at the portfolio component level and then rolled up to the portfolio level to determine overall portfolio impact. In order to develop meaningful measures, metrics should be SMART (Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Realistic, Timebound) ((Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 6.1.2.1, Pg# 89)

questions.text: Julia Thomas, a stakeholder in your organization has complained to you that she did not receive the portfolio information that she needed. What should you do first as the Portfolio Manager?
questions.explanation:
Review of Communication Management plan makes sense here, as it documents who will receive what information, at what time, and in what format (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 7.1.3.1, Pg# 113)

- Communication Strategy Matrix review is not needed here, as SH needs have not really changed
- Stakeholder Matrix review is not needed here, the scenario does not talk about any change in SH needs
- The scenario here does not warrant a risk situation, may be the RR needs to be updated as a result of CMP review. However, if the case be, this will happen later

questions.text: Decision is made to cancel the SMS Banking sub-portfolio in Digital Banking portfolio, as it no longer meets the market demand and target revenue. What is your next step as a Portfolio Manager?

options.text: Submit a change request through the change control process
Start terminating the components and return back the financials and remaining resources to the resource pool
Analyze the impact of this change w.r.t. the organizational objectives
Submit an updated component business case to portfolio governance board on how the components can contribute positively to portfolio objectives

questions.explanation:
As the sub-portfolio termination decision is done by PGB, the next step by Portfolio Manager is to start returning the financials and resources back to organizational resource pool, so that they could be reallocated to active portfolio components to better meet organizational vision and objectives

- Component termination decision has already been made. The impact must have been determined before the decision was taken by PGB. Also, at this point, there is no point of re-submitting sub-portfolio BC to PGB or follow the change control process

questions.text: Which of the following is updated as a Portfolio Process Assets (PPAs)?

options.text: Strategic alignment, Knowledge Repositories, change management and stakeholder risks
Portfolio records and documents, portfolio component closure information and portfolio component selection decisions
Component proposals, investments, organization calendars, risk register

questions.explanation:
Portfolio process assets (PPA) include process-related assets, from the portfolio stakeholders that can be used to influence the portfolio's success. These process assets include formal and informal plans, policies, procedures, and guidelines. The process assets also include the portfolio related knowledge bases, such as lessons learned and historical information. Portfolio process assets may include information on tools, techniques, models, integrated schedules, and risk and performance data (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 36,37)

Hint: For exam, know the PPA contents from Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed
- The other choices Organizational Calendars, Knowledge Repositories, and Employee Reviews are part of OPAs

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager of the City Renovation portfolio in Bin Laden organization. You are currently in the process of defining portfolio strategy. What portfolio key deliverable is a representative of portfolio vision, timeline, and dependencies?
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Roadmap certainly has timeline and dependencies. Portfolio Roadmap provides the high-level strategic direction (i.e. vision) and information in a chronological fashion for portfolio management execution and ensures that dependencies within the portfolio are established and evaluated (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 4.3.3.1, Table 3-2, Pg# 39,51)

- Strategic plan has vision and dependencies, but not timeline
- Portfolio Management plan establishes how a portfolio is defined, organized, optimized and controlled
- Portfolio Charter has dependencies, may have vision, but not timeline

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager, you perform several activities to ensure that the portfolio remains aligned with the organizational strategic objectives. While optimizing your portfolio, you have noticed that one of your components is misaligned w.r.t. the organizational objectives and needs to be cancelled. There is enough money remaining after the cancellation of this component. What will be your course of action?

options.text: Arrange meeting with the portfolio sponsor and discuss how could the resources can be distributed to the other components based on need
Arrange meeting with the portfolio governance board and discuss with them how could the resources can be distributed to the other components based on need
Arrange meeting with the senior management and discuss with them how could the resources be distributed to the other components based on need

questions.explanation:
‘Authorize Portfolio’ is a governance management process in which PGB makes decision of reallocation of funding and resources from deactivated and terminated components to the active portfolio components or send them back to the organization resource pool

- Reallocation of funds and portfolio resources is not the responsibility of Portfolio Manager, Sponsor or Senior Management. Portfolio Manager can only suggest the best possible resource utilization to the PGB

questions.text: A plan of goals, policies, and actions that represent the overall direction and focus of the organization, is referred to as:
questions.explanation:
Organizational vision and mission go as input to Organizational strategic planning exercise, the result of which comes as Organizational Strategic Plan. Organizational Strategy and objectives are stated in that plan, and this plan is a representative of organization's vision, mission and direction. Organizational Strategy and objectives makes the key input to Portfolio Strategic planning exercise

- Organizational vision represents the direction and goals of organization
- Organizational mission represents the action steps to achieve the goals and vision of organization
- Portfolio Vision is derived from organizational strategy and objectives, and is stated in Portfolio Strategic plan

questions.text:
What can you tell about the following portfolio status, having CPI weight = 80% and SPI weight = 20%?

| Portfolio Component | NPV | CPI | SPI |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Component-A | 3 | 1.3 | 1.2 |
| Component-B | 2 | 0.95 | 1.3 |
| Component-C | 1.5 | 1 | 0.9 |
| Component-D | 12 | 1 | 1 |
| Component-E | 6 | 0.9 | 0.8 |

options.text: Work is not performing well and outside of range
Work is progressing as planned and within range
Work is progressing as planned but outside range
Work is not preforming well but within range

questions.explanation:
Composite Index needs to be calculated to get to know the Portfolio current status. 
A ratio of 1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned and within range. A ratio of >1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned, but outside the usual range (i.e. 1.0). A ratio <1.0 suggests that work is not progressing as planned (i.e. 1.0)

Portfolio Composite Index (CI) / Critical Ratio (CR) = Sum [(NPV / Sum(NPVs)) * ((CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight))]
when NPV is not present in the calculation, then Portfolio CI = Sum [(CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight)]

questions.text: While managing a program for the banking sector spanning multiple transformational areas. A new portfolio manager comes to you seeking advice on the usefulness of ROI. You tell her that ROI is the best method to measure returns of:
questions.explanation: As a rule of thumb and based on numerous studies: ROI is used for investments with short duration and low risk. IRR is used for investments with long duration and low risk. For high risk investments, incremental IRR and other methods can be used.

questions.text: Organizational structure, governance, hierarchy & culture, stakeholder risk tolerances are considered as
questions.explanation:
Organizational structure, governance processes, hierarchy & culture, stakeholder risk tolerances, marketplace conditions, regulations, legal constraints, organizational project management are examples of EEF (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 3.2.1.4, Pg# 38)

Hint: For exam, it is very important to know the examples of EEFs from Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed

questions.text: The Cumulative Frequency Distribution (S-curve) is a modelling/simulation technique (Monte Carlo Analysis) used to estimate the probability of achieving specific objectives. In the S-curve below, what is the probability of meeting the cost objective of $38.75?
questions.explanation: $38.75 meets the S-curve graph at around 10% on y-axis (Probability of achieving the Cost target) (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 132,133)

questions.text: Major organizational structural changes are now in place in Yokohama LLC, following the acquiring of Abheja Enterprises. Several changes in Yokohama LLC Organizational Strategic plan has been made, and has been updated in the Organizational Process Assets(OPAs). Which tool and technique is used in the portfolio management process that may update OPAs?
questions.explanation: Only 2 Portfolio Management processes have OPAs updates in the output i.e ‘Develop Risk Management Plan’ and ‘Manage Portfolio Risks’ (both Risk Management processes). Graphical Analytical Methods is one of the T&T of Develop Portfolio Risk Management Plan process, where Probability and Impact matrix is developed. This Probability & Impact matrix may be updated in OPAs (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 4.3.3.1, Pg# 39,51)

questions.text: Recently, there has been major changes in your e-learning organization executive management and the CEO was fired for non performance. A new CEO, James Smith was appointed and will join duty in the coming week. What will the most likely thing portfolio manager do in this case?

options.text: Meet with PGB to discuss the issue
No action is required from the Portfolio Manager side
Add him to the stakeholder register
Document the situation as potential risk in risk register

questions.explanation:
The most likely thing that Portfolio Manager would do is to document the situation as a potential risk in the Risk Register (Refer Risk Register in Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 130,131)

- There is no mention of an issue situation in this scenario, and if there is any, this discussion is going to be at later step. In case of issue, the first thing the Portfolio Manager would do is to document it in Issue Register
- Portfolio Manager is supposed to take the ownership of every situation in the portfolio and take necessary actions as per the requirements
d) Adding CEO to the stakeholder register can be an option for later

questions.text: Few of your key portfolio stakeholders are complaining that they are receiving redundant information in portfolio reports. What will be your best course of action as a Portfolio Manager?

options.text: Remove the stakeholders from Portfolio Communication matrix
Emphasize to the stakeholders about the importance of provided information in reports

questions.explanation:
Communication Requirement Analysis under Manage Portfolio Information process deals with the redundant information to make the data meaningful and fit for purpose. The result will be updated in Communication Management plan (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 117)

- Removing the stakeholders is not going to help in this scenario
- As the information is redundant in reports, Portfolio Manager needs to work on its resolution
- It is Portfolio Manager's responsibility to own this issue. Escalation to PGB should be the last resort, and must be done as per the issue escalation criteria defined in the Governance model in Portfolio Management plan

questions.text: Where is the most efficient portfolio located?
questions.explanation:
Portfolio B is the most efficient portfolio as it lies on the efficient frontier curve.

- An efficient portfolio can never be above the curve so Portfolio C is not an option.
- Portfolio A, D and E are inefficient as they lie below the curve.

questions.text: Which tool & technique and portfolio management process are used to understand the human, financial and asset resource requirements of portfolio?

options.text: Stakeholder Analysis, Develop Portfolio Communication Management plan
Capability and Capacity Analysis, Manage Supply & Demand

questions.explanation:
The Capability and Capacity Analysis in ‘Manage Supply & Demand’ process studies the capability (e.g., skill sets and certifications) and capacity (i.e. supply) of resources (i.e. asset, human, financial) to meet the portfolio demands (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 6.2.2.3, Pg# 95)

- The purpose of Stakeholder Analysis in ‘Develop Portfolio Communication Management plan’ process is to identify the stakeholders, determine the different individuals and groups, and determine their concerns, interests, and influence.
- The Cost-Benefit Analysis in ‘Manage Portfolio Value’ process (as part of Value Scoring and Measurement Analysis) defines the benefits that will be provided by the portfolio and compare it to the costs of the portfolio. Benefits may be tangible or intangible
- This Scenario Analysis method in ‘Optimize Portfolio’ process (as part of Quantitative and Qualitative Analysis) enables decision makers to create a variety of portfolio scenarios using different combinations of both potential and current portfolio components and evaluating their possible outcomes.

questions.text:
Consider the following Multi-Criteria Weighted ranking table for 3 projects A, B, C in your portfolio XYZ Answer the following
- What is the component score for project C?
- What is the order of priority of 3 projects, A, B, C?

| Project | Criteria 1 (Revenue Generation) | Rank 1 | Criteria 2 (Market Share) | Rank 2 | Criteria 3 (ROI) | Rank 3 |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Project A | 10K USD | | 60% | | 25% | |
| Project B | 20K USD | | 40% | | 55% | |
| Project C | 30K USD | | 20% | | 10% | |
questions.explanation:
To select the criteria rank: for Revenue, Market Share, and ROI criteria, the highest number for a project gets the highest rank (1). Accordingly, 1 (highest), 2 (second-highest), and 3 (lowest) ranks are assigned.

Assigning ranks based on the values:
- Criteria 1 (Revenue): C (30K) = 1, B (20K) = 2, A (10K) = 3
- Criteria 2 (Market Share): A (60%) = 1, B (40%) = 2, C (20%) = 3
- Criteria 3 (ROI): B (55%) = 1, A (25%) = 2, C (10%) = 3

Calculating Project Scores (Simple Average of ranks):
- Project A: (3 + 1 + 2) / 3 = 2
- Project B: (2 + 2 + 1) / 3 = 1.67
- Project C: (1 + 3 + 3) / 3 = 2.33

a) Project C score = 2.33
b) In a Multi-criteria Weighted Ranking model, the lower the component score, the higher the priority. Based on the scores (B: 1.67, A: 2.0, C: 2.33), the priority order is B, A, C.

questions.text: Ms. Rida has appointed as Portfolio Manager for a new portfolio under development. In developing the portfolio, she needs access to information on the organization long-term direction, vision, goals, and objectives. Where will Ms. Rida find this information?
questions.explanation:
Organizational strategy and objectives provide organization's long-term direction, vision, mission, strategy, goals, and objectives

- Portfolio Strategic plan contains portfolio vision, objectives and goals, and aligns the portfolio strategy to the organizational strategy and objectives
- Portfolio Charter authorizes the portfolio manager to apply portfolio resources to portfolio components. It contains the portfolio structure and determines how the Portfolio will deliver value to the organization.
- Organizational governance is the process by which an organization directs and controls its operational and strategic activities

questions.text: There are two regulatory components to be added to your Environmental Health portfolio. One of the components will address reduced CO2 emission and the second component will address wildlife protection. In order to start these components in the portfolio, GO decision will be received from:
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Governance body is made up of one or more individuals that ensures decision making (Go/No-go), alignment of portfolio components to organizational strategic objectives, component authorization (initiation, termination, changes) and portfolio oversight (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 19)

- Sponsor is already part of governance board, he may be involved in decision making as part of PGB
- Portfolio manager may guide the selection, prioritization, and termination of portfolio components in phase gate meetings, however, the ultimate decision is taken by PGB
- CEO is not directly responsible for portfolio related decision making, he may be involved in decision making as part of PGB

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager, you perform several activities to ensure that the portfolio remains aligned with the organizational strategic objectives. These activities include risk management, performance monitoring, resource capacity management, component governance, strategic alignment and portfolio communication management. From the below choices, which of the following is considered as the role of the Portfolio Management Office (PMO)?

options.text: Developing Templates, Checklists, and providing Knowledge Management
Effective planning, execution and monitoring of components as per the objectives
Reallocation of resources among portfolio components

questions.explanation:
Portfolio Management Office (PMO) is responsible for providing standardization in the portfolio (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 17,18)

Hint: For exam, know the roles and responsibility of Portfolio Manager, Sponsor, PGB and PMO from Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed

- Meeting legal and regulatory requirements is roles and responsibility of Portfolio Manager
- Reallocation of resources among portfolio components is roles and responsibility of Portfolio Governance Board, as part of Authorize Portfolio process
- Planning, execution and monitoring of components as per the objectives is roles and responsibility of Component Managers (Project and Program Managers)

questions.text: The document which defines how the portfolio will be defined, executed, monitored, and controlled to meet the organizational strategy and objectives is termed as:
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Management Plan development is an iterative process and includes the integration of subsidiary plans such as performance, communication, and risk management plans. The portfolio management plan establishes how a portfolio is defined, organized, optimized, and controlled (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.1, Pg# 57)

- Portfolio Performance Management plan describes how and when the portfolio resources will be planned, balanced, and allocated to the portfolio components, how the portfolio component progress will be measured towards realization of portfolio objectives, and how cost-effective resource allocations are made to maximize portfolio performance.
- Portfolio Strategic plan is a document that contains portfolio vision, objectives and goals, and aligns the portfolio strategy to the organizational strategy and objectives
- Portfolio charter is a document that authorizes the portfolio manager to apply portfolio resources to portfolio components. It contains the portfolio structure and determines how the Portfolio will deliver value to the organization.

questions.text: Amir is the Portfolio Manager of Al-Barakah Pvt Ltd. He has just completed the Develop Portfolio Performance Management Plan process. Where would he record the performance metrics, performance roles and responsibilities, and the performance reporting tools information?
questions.explanation: As an output of 'Develop Portfolio performance Management plan' process, Performance Management plan is created, and gets updated as a subsidiary plan in 'Portfolio Management plan' using the 'Integration of Portfolio Management plans' T&T. Performance metrics, Performance roles and responsibilities, and Performance reporting tools are contents of Portfolio Performance Management plan ((Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 6.1.3.1, Pg# 91)

questions.text: In a portfolio you have a continuous interaction between the portfolio and its components. You have to follow a lot of processes and procedures in order to reach a satisfactory result. In your opinion as a portfolio manager, who guides the portfolio team to follow the processes, metrics, and other procedures in the portfolio?
questions.explanation:
the person who guides the portfolio team should be the Portfolio Manager. He manages the portfolio team to implement and follow the different processes and procedures in the portfolio (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 14, 15)

- PMO is responsible for standardisation in the portfolio and to develop and maintain portfolio management framework and methodology
- Though Portfolio Sponsor is responsible and accountable for the success of the portfolio, however, a Portfolio Sponsor is normally an executive who has a lot of obligations and does not have the luxury of time to follow up regularly on the team. Thus, the Sponsor follows up with the portfolio manager on the progress and only intervenes in the case where there is a big issue that the portfolio manager can not solve. Sponsor is also a definite member of PGB
- CEO is not responsible to implement processes and procedures in portfolio

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently working on establishing how your portfolio will be defined, organized, optimized and controlled. To which of the following sections in the Portfolio Management Plan will you refer to reflect changes based on costs, requirements and schedule?
questions.explanation:
Change Control and Management section in PMP defines the process of managing portfolio changes to approved scope and requirements, schedules, and funding, including review and approval by stakeholders and governing bodies. (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.1.3.2, Pg# 63)

- Manage Strategic Change section in PMP responds to the changes in organizational strategy and objectives. In this scenario, there is no mention of change in portfolio strategic direction
- Procurement Planning section defines any portfolio level procurement directives or standards that will be leveraged and which should be considered when managing the portfolio
- Performance Management section includes measuring and monitoring performance and value, portfolio performance reporting, and review

questions.text: Mr. Amir, the Program Manager of one of the programs in your Website Development portfolio is unable to reach to a Design vendor by email or phone call, to inform him of a recent PMO approval on a Design tool so that vendor could immediately start working on the design of a time-critical program component. Program Manager has escalated the issue to you for assistance. What will you do as a Portfolio Manager?

options.text: Meet the Design vendor in his office and try to resolve the issue
Send a formal letter to Design vendor
Inform Program Manager to seek support at Program level since this is not a concern to Portfolio Management
Escalate the issue to Portfolio Governance Board

questions.explanation:
The best choice for Portfolio Manager in this situation is to visit Design vendor at his office (may be in the presence of Program Manager) to communicate the PMO approval and to resolve the need at hand promptly

- Program Manager had tried to solve the situation himself with no luck. Portfolio Manager in his role would try to assist Program Manager, as the issue is of importance and may be critical to the overall health of the portfolio.
- Program Manager had already tried calling and emailing the vendor with no luck. He needs immediate response from vendor, sending a letter and expecting a response on it may be time consuming.
- Portfolio Manager would first try to resolve the issue at his end. Escalation to PGB should always be the last resort

questions.text: Due to the impact of Covid19 pandemic, your CEO has announced a 25% cut to the budget allocation of your portfolio. As the Portfolio manager, which aspect of the Portfolio Management planning will you consult first to manage this change?
questions.explanation:
Change Control and Management defines the process of managing portfolio changes to approved scope and requirements, schedules, and funding, including review and approval by stakeholders and governing bodies. As per the scenario given in the question, Portfolio Manager will first consult this section to make changes in the budget allocation (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.1.3.2, Pg# 63)

- Governance model establishes the decision-making rights and authorities, roles, responsibilities, rules, and protocols needed to manage progress towards the achievement of their organizational strategy and objectives. In this scenario, this doesn’t need to be consulted
- Portfolio balancing supports the ability to plan and allocate resources according to strategic direction and the ability to maximize portfolio return. In this scenario, this area may be consulted in portfolio but at later stages
- Manage Strategic Change responds to the changes in organizational strategy and objectives. In this scenario, there is no mention of change in portfolio strategic direction

questions.text:
The Portfolio Manager has updated the financial matrix table for 5 programs. The updated NPV and probability of success are listed in the following table. Which enterprise NPV ranking (from highest to lowest) should the Portfolio Manager present to executive committee?

Program | NPV (in M$) | Probability | Product Launch per year
--- | --- | --- | ---
A | 800 | 0.8 | 1
B | 1,000 | 0.5 | 2
C | 6,500 | 0.6 | 1
D | 5,000 | 0.3 | 1
E | 8,000 | 0.45 | 2
questions.explanation:
Expected Monetary Value (EMV) = Probability X Impact (NPV)
EMV (Program A): (0.8 x 800) = 640
EMV (Program B): (0.5 x 1000) = 500
EMV (Program C): (0.6 x 6500) = 3900
EMV (Program D): (0.3 x 5000) = 1500
EMV (Program E): (0.45 x 8000) = 3600

The highest the EMV, the highest the priority i.e. order of program prioritization is C, E, D, A, B
Note: 'Product Launch per year' factor in the provided data has no contribution in the calculation of initiative prioritization, and is a total distractor here

questions.text: Sensitivity Analysis helps to determine which risk has the most potential impact on the portfolio. In the Tornado diagram below, which risk has the most impact on the organizational objective of "Profitability"?
questions.explanation: Sensitivity analysis helps to determine which risks have the most potential impact/variability on the portfolio. Tornado diagram displays the contribution of the identified risks to the value of one strategic objective (Profitability in this case). Keyword for Sensitivity Analysis is "Impact". Here Risk 4 may impact 25B of profit range (10B threat, 15B opportunity), which has the huge impact on the Profitability objective of all the available risks. (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 132,133)

questions.text: Your company's new CEO has set an aggressive target and informed everyone that the target needs to be met by all means in order for the company to be able to realize benefits and avoid bankruptcy. What is the best management approach that the portfolio manager should take in this case?
questions.explanation: You, as a Portfolio Manager are not in a normal situation here, the situation is critical and the target needs to be met by all means. For this you must use a directing management style in order to be able to realize the targets and strategic objectives; all other options are secondary in this particular scenario. So you will mainly be directing in order to avoid delays and manage conflicts quickly. However when required, you can use other options in combination of the Directing approach. This comes as part of your role in governance

questions.text: The Secretary to the CEO of your organization informs you that the CEO is not receiving any portfolio reports. She informs you that the CEO is interested in the monthly portfolio performance reports. What will you do as portfolio manager?

options.text: Inform the CEO to follow the Portfolio issue escalation process
Meet with CEO to determine his information need
Arrange meeting with the Secretary to determine CEO communication needs
Update the Communication Matrix with information provided by CEO Secretary

questions.explanation:
The best course of action for Portfolio Manager in this scenario is to meet CEO in person to determine his communication needs in detail, and then update the Communication Matrix accordingly

- It is quite possible that Secretary is not correctly communicating the communication requirements of CEO and may be missing some information needs as well, the best choice is to meet CEO in person
- Secretary may arrange the meeting with Portfolio Manager and CEO, however, meeting with Secretary is not going to really help to understand CEO communication needs
- If stakeholders are not receiving portfolio communications as per expectations, then this comes under the Portfolio Manager ownership to resolve the situation

questions.text: Which among the following is the role and responsibility of Portfolio Sponsor in your organization?

options.text: Engages stakeholders in projects and programs

questions.explanation:
A sponsor is a person or group who provides resources for the portfolio, and is accountable for enabling success. Sponsors champion the approval of portfolio components (projects, programs, and operations). Once the portfolio component is approved, the sponsor helps ensure that the components perform according to organizational strategy and objectives. Sponsors also recommend portfolio component changes or closures to align with organizational strategic changes. Note: Sponsor is usually the a member of PGB (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 19, 20)

- Engaging stakeholders in projects and programsis the role and responsibility of component managers (Project and Program Management)
- Portfolio Governance body ensures decision making, alignment of portfolio components to organizational strategic objectives, component authorization and portfolio oversight
- Guiding the selection of components is the role and responsibility of Portfolio Manager

questions.text:
Calculate the composite index of the following portfolio, having CPI weight = 80% and SPI weight = 20%

| Portfolio Component | NPV | CPI | SPI |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Component-A | 3 | 1.3 | 1.2 |
| Component-B | 2 | 0.95 | 1.3 |
| Component-C | 1.5 | 1 | 0.9 |
| Component-D | 12 | 1 | 1 |
| Component-E | 6 | 0.9 | 0.8 |
questions.explanation:
A ratio of 1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned and expected. A ratio of >1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned, but outside the usual range (i.e. 1.0). A ratio <1.0 suggests that work is not progressing as planned (i.e. 1.0)

Portfolio Composite Index (CI) / Critical Ratio (CR) = Sum [(NPV / Sum(NPVs)) * ((CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight))]
When NPV is not present in the calculation, then Portfolio CI = Avg [(CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight)]

Detailed Calculation is present in the table provided in the explanation. CPI & SPI weights are 80% and 20% respectively.
Composite Index of given portfolio is 1.005 ~ 1.0
Note: This is a very important and tricky questions for the exam. Do practice it before sitting in the real exam.

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently working on defining the portfolio governance. What are the key activities carried out during the “Develop Portfolio Management Plan” process?

options.text: Create the Portfolio Management Plan, Portfolio Strategic Plan updates
Portfolio Strategic Plan updates, Portfolio process assets updates
Create the Portfolio Management Plan, Develop Portfolio Structure
Create the Portfolio Management Plan, Develop the Portfolio Management Organization Structure

questions.explanation: The purpose of 'Develop Portfolio Management plan' process is to develop the portfolio management organization structure, and create the portfolio management plan (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Review initial para of section Chp 5, Pg# 57)

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in Dar-ul-Ilm portfolio. You are currently collaborating and facilitating with your portfolio stakeholders to define portfolio communication management plan. The following outputs are produced as a result of Stakeholder Analysis technique?

options.text: Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix
Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix, Communication Matrix
Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix
Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix, Communication Matrix

questions.explanation:
‘Stakeholder Analysis’ technique in Develop Portfolio Communication Management plan produces Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix and Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 111)

- ‘Communication Matrix’ is an output of Communication Requirement Analysis in Develop Portfolio Communication Management plan

questions.text:
Based on the component and aggregated performance data of ABC portfolio provided in the below table, what can you tell about the current progress of Portfolio ABC?

Portfolio | CV | CPI | SPI | BAC
Project A | 100 | 1.5 | 0.8 | 1000
Program B | 50 | 2 | 0.5 | 500
Project C | 50 | 1.8 | 0.7 | 800
Total | 200 | 1.76 | 0.66 | 2300

options.text: Portfolio ABC is late and spent less than planned
No information can be drawn from this data
Portfolio ABC is early and spent less than planned
Portfolio ABC is ahead of schedule and spent more than planned

questions.explanation:
Currently, Portfolio ABC CPI>1 and SPI<0, accordingly portfolio is late (behind schedule) on schedule side but has underspent so far.

Rules for Portfolio Health:
CPI (Cost Performance Index)
>1: under budget
=1: on budget
<1: over budget

SPI (Schedule Performance Index)
>1: ahead of schedule
=1: on schedule
<1: behind schedule

questions.text: An identified risk has occurred in your portfolio and has become an issue now. Which document will you consult to establish accountability for this risk?
questions.explanation:
Risk accountability and ownership is documented in the Risk Register. Risk owner's role is to ensure analysis and, as necessary, to assign response-related actions, and to monitor the situation for as long as the risk is current (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, check Risk Register contents in Section 8.2.1.1, Pg# 130, 131)

- Risk management plan has ownership regarding activities regarding risk management processes, but not for individual risks
- Issue Register does not have risk ownership
- Portfolio Management plan has R&R and ownership regarding overall portfolio management and governance related activities

questions.text: You are currently working as the Portfolio Manager of Design portfolio. You have recently setup an automated software tool, Confluence (by Atlassian) to support organizational visibility, standardization, process improvement and facilitating decision making. The manual or automated tools used for information collection and distribution to support the outcomes of the portfolio management process are termed as:
questions.explanation:
Overall explanation
Portfolio management information system (PMIS) consists of the tools (manual and automated) to gather, integrate, and disseminate the outputs of the portfolio management processes. These systems support overall organizational visibility, standardization, measurement, and process improvement, and can facilitate effective decision making by providing the organization with key performance metrics and target collection, analysis, and reporting (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 2.4, Pg# 25,26)

Hint: for exam, it is very important to know the definition, concept and types of PMIS as stated in Standard of Portfolio Management, 3rd ed

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently working on defining, aligning and authorizing the portfolio in support of organizational strategic objectives. Which document contains how your portfolio will be managed and roles and responsibilities across the portfolio components?
questions.explanation: Portfolio Management plan defines how the portfolio will be managed throughout the portfolio management processes. Governance Model section of PMP defines decision making rights, roles and responsibilities and protocols needed to manage portfolio progress towards the achievement of organizational strategy (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Review Governance Model in section 5.1.3.2, Pg# 62) - Portfolio Charter and Strategic Plan do not define portfolio roles and responsibilities

questions.text: The following outputs are linked to the Communication Requirement Analysis, under the Develop Communication Management Plan process?

options.text: Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix
Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix
Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix, Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix, Communication Matrix

questions.explanation:
‘Communication Matrix’ is an output of Communication Requirement Analysis in Develop Portfolio Communication Management plan (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 112)

- ‘Stakeholder Analysis’ technique in Develop Portfolio Communication Management Plan produces Stakeholder Register, Stakeholder Matrix and Stakeholder Communication Strategy Matrix

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. You are currently working on defining, aligning and authorizing the portfolio in support of organizational strategic objectives. What tool and technique is used to create the Portfolio Management Organization Structure?
questions.explanation: A technique used in ‘Develop Portfolio Management Plan’ process to produce the’ Portfolio Management Organizational Structure’. How the portfolio will be managed i.e. performance reviews, roles and responsibilities across components (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Review initial paras of section 5.1.2.2, Pg# 61)

questions.text: Which of the following describes the correct attributes of Portfolio and Programs?

options.text: Portfolio have end date, but programs keep on-going
Portfolio management is about to do the work right, its processes are not interrelated
Portfolio components may or may not have dependencies, but program components are always interrelated

questions.explanation:
Portfolio components may be related or may not be related, however, projects under program always need to be interrelated

- Programs have end date, so operational activities are separate and not considered part of programs
- Programs have have operational elements, that's why they don't get closed (unlike projects and program ) until they meet the organizational objectives they are created for
- Portfolio Management processes are interrelated to each other. Also, portfolio management is about to 'do the right work', and project and program management is about to 'do the work right'

questions.text: You are working as Portfolio Manager for Social Development portfolio in Sindh province. The portfolio is progressing as expected and PGB is overall satisfied with the portfolio value generation in the form of increased employment rate, literacy rate and no of hospitals in the region over the past year. Which analysis determines the effect of changing one or more factors of the Social Development portfolio?
questions.explanation:
Trade-off analysis determines the effect of changing one or more factors of the portfolio (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, check Investment choices in Section 8.1.2.3, Pg# 127)

Note: For exam, know the definition of all 6 Investment Choices as mentioned in Standard 3rd ed

- Time-to-market variability determines the effects of portfolio velocity.
- Performance variability analyzes the performance of the portfolio
- Market-payoff variability focuses on pricing and sales forecasts and depends on a number of marketing factors

questions.text: A new Portfolio Manager in your organization is currently preparing his Portfolio Charter and has come to you asking advice about what should be present in Charter. Your response would be:

options.text: Justification, Scenario Analysis, Capability & Capacity Analysis
All internal and external dependencies, components fixed timelines
Key dependencies, critical success criteria, high-level timelines

questions.explanation:
Portfolio Charter contains the portfolio objectives, portfolio justification, key and major stakeholders, stakeholder expectations and requirements, communication requirements, high-level scope, benefits, critical success criteria, resources, high-level timeline, and assumptions, constraints, dependencies, and risks (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 4.2.3.2, Pg# 49)

- ‘Justification’ is correct, however the other points in the options are tools and techniques used in ‘Develop portfolio Charter’ process, and not content.
- Portfolio Charter has key dependencies, but it contains high level timelines, not component fixed timelines

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager of the City Renovation portfolio in Bin Laden organization. You are currently in the process of defining portfolio strategy. Among the following, which input is used to develop the Portfolio Charter?
questions.explanation: Strategic plan is an input to ‘Develop Portfolio Charter’ process. The information in the strategic plan necessary for developing the portfolio charter is the portfolio vision and objectives, the benefits expected, and the key risks, prioritization model, dependencies, and constraints (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 4.2.1.1, Pg# 48)

questions.text: A risk has been identified on one of the projects of your portfolio. The risk response will require $500,000 and the allocated contingency fund for the complete project is $100,000. As a result, the required $500,000 contingency fund will impact the project budget. What will be your advice as the Portfolio Manager?

options.text: Ask project manager to remove the contingency funds from his project budget
Request project manager to access contingency funds from other components within the portfolio
Request project manager to access additional funds from the management reserves
Terminate the project since project budget exceeds project benefits

questions.explanation:
The portfolio provides equity protection for the portfolio components. Hence, the portfolio will provide for the shortfall in component contingency fund from the portfolio level contingency fund (Refer last paragraph of Risk Management from Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 120)

- Termination is not a choice here. Also, there is no mention in the scenario that the project benefits were not met
- Management reserves is used for unanticipated risks. The scenario is about an identified risk
- Project Manager can’t just ask for reserves from other components. He will look out for Portfolio Manager for that

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager of Al-Barakah Pvt Ltd. You have just completed the Develop Portfolio Performance Management Plan process. Which of the following tools and techniques have helped you to prepare for the performance metrics?
questions.explanation:
Performance metrics are defined in Develop Portfolio Performance Management plan process. Elicitation Techniques is one of the T&T of that process. Interviews, meetings, focus groups, surveys are different forms of eliciting information regarding portfolio performance metrics (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 6.1.2.1, Pg# 89)

- Capability and Capacity Analysis and PMIS are the T&Ts for Develop Portfolio Performance Management plan process. However, they are not helpful to prepare performance metrics

questions.text: Which of the below best describes the tools and techniques of Optimize Portfolio process?

options.text: Capability and Capacity Analysis, Graphical Analytical methods

questions.explanation:
C&C Analysis, Weighted Ranking and Scoring, Graphical Analytical methods, Q&Q Analysis are T&T of Optimize Portfolio process (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Fig 5-9, Pg# 72)

- Portfolio Component Inventory is a T&T of Define Portfolio process
- Portfolio Authorization technique and PMIS are T&T of Authorize Portfolio process
- Portfolio Report belong to Common Inputs and Outputs. It is not a T&T

questions.text:
You are a member of your organization's Program Governance Board(PGB). The Company's Strategic Plan includes five major goals, which are all weighted equally:

- Goal 1 is to fall within the time-to-market window;
- Goal 2 is to reduce operational costs;
- Goal 3 is to differentiate the products from other competitors in the market;
- Goal 4 is to deliver the highest quality product
- Goal 5 is to promote economic sustainability

At the next committee meeting, you will consider four programs and recommend only one out of them:
1. Program A partially supports goal 1, fully supports goals 2, 3 and 4, and does not support goal 5
2. Program B fully supports goals 1, 3, 4 and 5, but does not support goal 2
3. Program C fully supports goals 1 and 2, partially supports goals 3 and 4, but does not support goal 5
4. Program D partially supports goals 1, 2 and 5, and fully supports goals 3 and 4

With this information, which program will you recommend in PGB meeting?
questions.explanation:
Program B will be recommended. All Company goals are equal weights i.e. 20% for each 5 goals in the company. Based on the provided info, the following will be the program scoring and priorities corresponding to company goals:

- Program A: Goal 1 (10), Goal 2 (20), Goal 3 (20), Goal 4 (20), Goal 5 (0) = Total Score: 70, Priority: 2
- Program B: Goal 1 (20), Goal 2 (0), Goal 3 (20), Goal 4 (20), Goal 5 (20) = Total Score: 80, Priority: 1
- Program C: Goal 1 (20), Goal 2 (20), Goal 3 (10), Goal 4 (10), Goal 5 (0) = Total Score: 60, Priority: 3
- Program D: Goal 1 (10), Goal 2 (10), Goal 3 (20), Goal 4 (20), Goal 5 (10) = Total Score: 70, Priority: 2

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager, you perform several activities to ensure that the portfolio remains aligned with the organizational strategic objectives. These activities include risk management, performance monitoring, resource capacity management, component governance, strategic alignment and portfolio communication management. From the below choices, which of the following is considered as the role of the Portfolio Manager?

options.text: Supporting senior stakeholders in decision making by providing prompt portfolio information
Authorizing the initiation of portfolio component
Developing and maintaining portfolio management framework and methodology

questions.explanation:
Portfolio Manager supports senior-level decision making by ensuring timely and consistent communication to stakeholders on progress, changes, and impact on portfolio components (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 14,15)

Hint: For exam, know the roles and responsibility of Portfolio Manager, Sponsor, PGB and PMO from Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed

- Resource reallocation and authorization of components are roles and responsibility of Portfolio Governance board
- Developing and maintaining of portfolio management methodology is the roles and responsibility of Portfolio Management Office (PMO)

questions.text: Two of your key stakeholders, Mr James Warner and Mike Thompson have complained to you that they are lacking needed information about resources not properly allocated on two components in your portfolio. This could have been avoided with:
questions.explanation:
Stakeholders are lacking information about component resources. This could have been avoided by proper resource management

- The other choices are not best in this case

questions.text:
Calculate the composite index of the following portfolio, having CPI weight = 80% and SPI weight = 20%

Portfolio Component | NPV | CPI | SPI
--- | --- | --- | ---
Component-A | 3 | 1.3 | 1.2
Component-B | 2 | 0.95 | 1.3
Component-C | 1.5 | 1 | 0.9
Component-D | 12 | 1 | 1
Component-E | 6 | 0.9 | 0.8
questions.explanation:
A ratio of 1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned and expected. A ratio of >1.0 suggests that work is progressing as planned, but outside the usual range (i.e. 1.0). A ratio <1.0 suggests that work is not progressing as planned (i.e. 1.0)

Portfolio Composite Index (CI) / Critical Ratio (CR) = Sum [(NPV / Sum(NPVs)) * ((CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight))]

When NPV is not present in the calculation, then Portfolio CI = Avg [(CPI * weight) + (SPI * weight)]

Detailed Calculation is based on the weights given (CPI=80%, SPI=20%). 
1. First, calculate the total NPV: 3 + 2 + 1.5 + 12 + 6 = 24.5.
2. Calculate the relative weight of each component based on NPV (e.g., Component-A: 3 / 24.5 ≈ 0.12245).
3. Calculate the weighted performance index for each component: ((CPI * 0.8) + (SPI * 0.2)).
4. Sum the products of (Component NPV weight * Component performance index) to get the overall Portfolio Composite Index.

From the detailed calculation: Composite Index of given portfolio is 1.005 ~ 1.0
Note: This is a very important and tricky question for the exam. Do practice it before sitting in the real exam.

questions.text: You are working as Portfolio Manager in the ERP portfolio of Al-Hamd organization. A specialized Consultant is assigned to multiple projects in your portfolio. Which of the following will help you to analyse the resource over and under allocations?
questions.explanation:
Resource Histogram aids in identifying portfolio risk associated with the resource over or under-allocations across the portfolio (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 118)

- The other choices are techniques for Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis T&T for Manage Supply and Demand process

questions.text: You have recently joined as Portfolio Manager in the Oman Ministry of Finance. The Ministry has mandated you to implement the PMI Portfolio Management framework and methodology. You have received approval of the Portfolio Management Implementation Plan. What is the first logical step you will take now?

options.text: Conduct an assessment of the current portfolio management
Communicate the Portfolio Management Implementation Plan
Train stakeholders on tools and methodologies of Portfolio Management

questions.explanation:
This scenario describes the completion of second main step of Portfolio Management Process Implementation i.e. 'Define the Portfolio Management Vision and Plan', and start of third main step i.e. 'Implement the Portfolio Management processes', the first logical sub-step of which is 'Define roles and responsibilities for portfolio management process implementation' (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 2.2.3, Pg# 24)

- 'Conduct an assessment of the current portfolio management' is the first main step of Portfolio Management Process Implementation, which is not the case here
- 'Communicate the Portfolio Management Implementation Plan' is the second logical sub-step of the 'Implement the Portfolio Management processes' main step of Portfolio Management Process Implementation
- 'Train stakeholders on tools and methodologies of Portfolio Management' is the third logical sub-step of the 'Implement the Portfolio Management processes' main step of Portfolio Management Process Implementation

questions.text: The Balanced Scorecard (BSC) consists of which of the following components:

options.text: Learning and Growth, Finance, Customers, Business Processes

questions.explanation:
Balanced Scorecard (BSC) refers to a strategic management performance metric used to identify and improve various internal business functions and their resulting external outcomes. The four legs of BSC include: 
1. Learning and growth
2. Business processes
3. Customers
4. Finance
Hint: Knowing the definition, purpose and 04 components of Balanced Scorecard is very important for For exam purpose

questions.text: The Benefit Realization of the components in your portfolio is defined in:
questions.explanation:
Performance Management plan has Benefits realization (how will realized benefits be tracked and compared to plans; how will value be calculated) as content (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 6.1.3.1, Pg# 91)

- The other choices are incorrect, as Strategic, Communication and Risk Management plans do not have benefits realization as contents

questions.text: The existing portfolio manager win your organization has been replaced by a new portfolio manager and the analysis shows that the distance between the pessimistic and best-case scenario of the new portfolio manager is larger than the old one, which kind of manager is the new one?
questions.explanation:
The distance between the pessimistic and the best case scenario highlights the level of risk one can take. If the level of risk is low (risk-averse), then the distance is closer; on another hand, if the level of risk taken is high (risk-taker), then the distance is larger

Note: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed is just a reference guide for the exam, so you will definitely have questions from outside the guide in the exam as well

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager for Al-Jazeera Pvt Ltd, you are working on portfolio management processes to manage and optimize the portfolio. Which of the following portfolio management process groups are you involved in?
questions.explanation:
Aligning Process Group consists of processes to manage and optimize the portfolio. This process group determines how portfolio components will be categorized, evaluated, selected for inclusion, modification, or elimination in the portfolio. The processes in this process group enable a structured method for aligning the mix of portfolio components to the organization’s strategy (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 3.1.2, Pg# 32)

- Defining Process Group consists of processes to establish how the organizational strategic objectives will be implemented in a portfolio; determines the portfolio strategic plan, charter, roadmap, portfolio management plan and subsidiary plans.
- Authorizing and Controlling Process Group consists of the processes for determining how PGB will authorize the portfolio and provides ongoing portfolio oversight. The two processes in this group are central to all the portfolio management processes and are the activities necessary to enable the portfolio as a whole to achieve business value to the organization.
- There doesn't exist anything like Quality process group in portfolio management

questions.text: The Chairperson of your portfolio governance board has complained to you that the monthly portfolio performance reports received by her contains redundant, inconsistent and inaccurate information. What will you do as the Portfolio Manager?
questions.explanation:
Overall explanation
Communication Req Analysis will be reviewed in this case during the 'Manage Portfolio Information' process to check if meaningful info has been extracted from raw communication data to present to key SHs such as Chairperson. Hint: One way to help make data meaningful is to build forecasts based on trends in the data (Note: This technique is very important from exam perspective). (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 7.2.2.3, Pg# 117)

- Commination Matrix has communication method, frequency and vehicles, which is not really a problem in this scenario
- CMP informs who will receive what information at what time in what format. None of these areas is a problem in this scenario
- Communication Strategy Matrix review does not make sense here as SH needs have not really changed

questions.text: Which of the following is not an input in developing the Portfolio Communication Management Plan?
questions.explanation: Portfolio Charter is not an input to Communication Management Plan. Hint: Once the Portfolio Management plan is established, Portfolio Strategic plan and Portfolio Charter is no more required as input to the development of any management plan (i.e risk, communication, performance). Portfolio Management plan has everything needed for the management, planning and execution of portfolio then. - PR is an input to CMP. Portfolio Communication management plan include information about interdependencies among the portfolio's components that could impact portfolio communication objectives. Those interdependencies come from Portfolio Roadmap - PPA is an input to CMP. PPA related to communication may include portfolio manager roles and responsibilities, status reports, governance decisions etc - PMP is an input to CMP. All elements of the Portfolio Management plan have communication requirements. Changes in the portfolio management plan may introduce new stakeholders or new communication requirements.

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager, you perform several activities to ensure that the portfolio remains aligned with the organizational strategic objectives. These activities include risk management, performance monitoring, resource capacity management, component governance, strategic alignment and portfolio communication management. From the below choices, which of the following is considered as the role of the Portfolio Sponsor?

options.text: Leading the approval of portfolio components
Reviewing, reallocating, reprioritizing and optimizing the portfolio components
Conducting training regarding portfolio management skills, tools etc

questions.explanation:
Portfolio Sponsor enables portfolio success, provide resources, and champions the approval of portfolio components (projects, programs, and operations). To ensure approval, Sponsor assists by supplying a viable component proposal to the portfolio governing body (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 19,20)
Hint: For exam, know the roles and responsibility of Portfolio Manager, Sponsor, PGB and PMO from Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed

- Reviewing, reallocating, reprioritizing and optimizing the portfolio components is the R&R of Portfolio Manager
- Conducting training regarding portfolio management skills, tools etc is the R&R of Portfolio Management Office (PMO)
- Providing portfolio oversight is R&R of Portfolio Governance board

questions.text: Communication Methods is one of the T&T under the ‘Manage Portfolio Information’ process. It refers to the methods to communicate Portfolio Information. Which of the below is not an example of Communication Methods?

options.text: Email, Video Conferencing tools, Web Portals

questions.explanation:
Communication Methods may include visual representations of the data and information receive such as dashboards, resource histograms, and a communication calendar. PMIS includes document repository and document version control systems etc. They do not constitute a good example of Communication Methods

- Email, Video Conferencing tools and Web Portals can be considered as Communication Methods
- Dashboards, Resource Histograms and Communication Calendars are examples of Communication Methods as per PMI Standard of Portfolio Management
- Dashboards is an example of Communication Methods as per PMI Standard of Portfolio Management

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager, you perform several activities to ensure that the portfolio remains aligned with the organizational strategic objectives. While optimizing your portfolio, you need to present to the portfolio governance board and senior management that how your components are ranked and balanced in a quantifiable manner throughout the portfolio. Which tool and technique will you use?
questions.explanation:
Multi-criteria Scoring model is a technique of Weighted Ranking and Scoring T&T in Optimize Portfolio process, that is used to score and rank portfolio components based on pre-established criteria and weights assigned to them (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.2.2.3, Pg# 69)

- Bubble Charts and Histograms are the analytical T&Ts of Optimize Portfolio process to present portfolio performance
- Prioritization Analysis is a T&T of Define Roadmap process, it performs the component prioritization at the high level, however, it does not involve the scoring and ranking process of component evaluation

questions.text: Portfolio Management Office (PMO) in your organization LMN Incorporation has recommended the implementation of PMIS in your XYZ portfolio. PMIS tool is used for?

options.text: Methods to gather and seek requirements for portfolio planning
Gather, integrate and distribute the outputs of portfolio management processes
Work breakdown structure of program, project and operations
A way to communicate messages on portfolio progress

questions.explanation:
Portfolio Management Information Systems are tools to gather, integrate and distribute the outputs of portfolio management processes (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 25,26)

Hint: For exam, know the types of PMIS as mentioned in Standard 3rd ed

- Portfolio Dashboards are a way to communicate messages on portfolio progress
- Elicitation techniques are methods to gather and seek requirements for portfolio planning
- WBS for project and program scope management is a wrong choice

questions.text: Sensitivity Analysis helps to determine which risk has the most potential impact on the portfolio. In the Tornado diagram below, which risk has the least impact on the organizational objective of "Profitability"?
questions.explanation:
Sensitivity analysis helps to determine which risks have the most potential impact/variability on the portfolio. Tornado diagram displays the contribution of the identified risks to the value of one strategic objective (Profitability in this case). Keyword for Sensitivity Analysis is “Impact”.
Here Risk 5 may impact around 2-3B of profit range (opportunity only), which has the least impact on the Profitability objective of all the available risks. (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 132,133)

questions.text: An opportunity was identified which can have a huge favourable impact on your portfolio. What will the portfolio manager do first?

options.text: Take measure to enhance the opportunity

questions.explanation:
Whenever a portfolio risk(positive or negative) is identified, the FIRST thing that a portfolio manager is supposed to do is to document it in the risk register

- Discussion with Sponsor, Portfolio team and PGB and the identification of options to exploit/enhance the opportunity (risk response plan) will be the choices for later

questions.text: As a result of COVID19 pandemic, your organization has initiated a change in direction, resulting in the re-definition of corporate goals and objectives. Which Portfolio Management tool and technique can be used during this process?
questions.explanation:
This scenario describes ‘Manage Strategic Change’ process, which has Gap Analysis technique. This analysis determines the gaps b/w ‘as-is’ and ‘to-be’ states of the portfolio, and changes needed in the portfolio mix in order that components may be added, changed, or terminated. (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 4.4.2.2, Pg# 54)

- Prioritization Analysis and Portfolio Component Inventory are T&T of Develop Portfolio Strategic Plan process
- Optimize Portfolio is a process, not a T&T

questions.text: Which of the following is portfolio component categorization criteria as per the Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed?

options.text: Portfolio component sponsor and Quantitative benefits
Increase in Profit and Business Efficiency Improvement

questions.explanation:
Increased Profitability and Efficiency Improvement are component categorization criteria (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 68)

- Portfolio component sponsor and Quantitative benefits are Portfolio component Identification criteria/Key descriptors
- Process Improvement is Categorization criteria, however, Urgency is Evaluation criteria
- Strategic Alignment is Evaluation criteria

questions.text:
The activities performed under the Develop Portfolio performance management plan include developing performance metrics to measure portfolio performance, defining portfolio value and resource management. The performance metrics define during this process include both tangible and intangible metrics.

Which of the following is an example of Quantitative (tangible) performance metric?

options.text: Percentage by which cycle times are reduced due to the portfolio

questions.explanation:
‘Percentage by which cycle times are reduced due to the portfolio’ is an example of Quantitative performance metric criteria (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Pg# 85,86)

Hint: For exam, know the examples of Quantitative (tangible) and Qualitative (intangible) performance metrics from the Standard of Portfolio Mgmt, 3rd ed

- The other choices are examples of Qualitative (intangible) performance metric criteria

questions.text: Which among the following is considered a Black Swan?

options.text: Hairline foot fracture from a slip, thunder storm

questions.explanation:
'Black Swan' are those risks which have low probability, however, if they are realized in a project, the impact can be huge and devastating. Plane crash, tsunami, thunder storm, earthquake are good examples of Black Swan risks

- project schedule delays, car accident, hairline fracture are not considered risks with low probability and high impact

questions.text: You are working as the Portfolio Manager of the City Renovation portfolio in Bin Laden organization. You are currently working to establish how the organizational strategic objectives will be implemented in a portfolio; determines the portfolio strategic plan, charter, roadmap, portfolio management plan and subsidiary plans. Which key deliverable(s) contain the Portfolio Prioritization model?

options.text: Portfolio Management plan, Portfolio Strategic plan

questions.explanation: You are currently working in the Defining process group. Portfolio Management plan and Stragetic plan both contain Prioritization model. Prioritzation model contains criteria to ensure alignment to organizational strategy and objectives, expected return on investment (ROI), investment risk, and dependencies (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.1.3.2, Pg# 64)

questions.text: Which tools and technique is used to link Risk Management plan as a subsidiary plan of Portfolio Management plan?
questions.explanation:
The subsidiary plans (risk, communication and performance management plans)are considered as part of the portfolio management plan although they may be separate documents and contain references to the portfolio management plan. ‘Integration of Portfolio Management plans’ is the technique used for the integration of subsidiary plans (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, section 5.1.2.3, Pg# 61,62)

- Portfolio Component Inventory is used to make a preliminary comparison of all inventoried portfolio components against the portfolio component definition to identify portfolio components that meet requirements for consideration.
- Portfolio organizational Structural Analysis (POSA) technique is used to produce the ‘Portfolio Management Organizational Structure (PMOS)’. It determines how the portfolio will be managed i.e. performance reviews, roles and responsibilities across components
- Interdependency Analysis identifies the dependencies the portfolio may have in relationship to other portfolios (external) or to the portfolio environment (internal). Dependencies to be analyzed may include resources, finance, quality, risks, timelines, etc.

questions.text: There was a strategic change in your portfolio and you have added two new components. The Portfolio vision has changed. In order to update the new vision, the dependencies and timeline for the components, you should update which of the following?
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Roadmap is a document that contain high level chronological graphical depiction of portfolio components, and contains milestones, timelines, deliverables and dependencies. Portfolio Roadmap is a representative of portfolio vision and direction

- Portfolio Charter is a document that authorizes the portfolio manager to apply portfolio resources to portfolio components. It contains the portfolio structure and determines how the Portfolio will deliver value to the organization.
- Portfolio Management Plan establishes how a portfolio is defined, organized, optimized, and controlled
- Portfolio Strategic plan is a document that contains portfolio vision, objectives and goals, key dependencies/risks and aligns the portfolio strategy to the organizational strategy and objectives, but it does not have component dependencies and timelines

questions.text: As the Portfolio Manager of VirtualTech portfolio at TGR organization, you have just updated the Portfolio, and created an updated list of portfolio components. In which portfolio management process are you working?
questions.explanation:
The purpose of the ‘Define Portfolio’ process is to create an up-to-date list of qualified portfolio components by identifying, categorizing, scoring, and ranking portfolio components(Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Review initial paras of section 5.2, Pg# 64)

- The ‘Portfolio’ that is created as a result of ‘Develop Portfolio Strategic plan’ process is just a high level initial list of components
- The other choices are wrong

questions.text: Which document aligns the strategic management of the portfolio to the organizational strategy and objectives?
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Strategic plan is a document that contains portfolio vision, objectives and goals, and aligns the portfolio strategy to the organizational strategy and objectives (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 4.1.3.1, Pg# 46)

- Portfolio Management Plan establishes how a portfolio is defined, organized, optimized, and controlled
- Portfolio Charter is a document that authorizes the portfolio manager to apply portfolio resources to portfolio components. It contains the portfolio structure and determines how the Portfolio will deliver value to the organization.
- Portfolio Roadmap is a document that contain high level chronological graphical depiction of portfolio components, and contains milestones, timelines, deliverables and dependencies. Portfolio Roadmap is a representative of portfolio direction

questions.text: Which document aligns the strategic management of the portfolio to the organizational strategy and objectives?
questions.explanation:
Portfolio Strategic plan is a document that contains portfolio vision, objectives and goals, and aligns the portfolio strategy to the organizational strategy and objectives (Reference: Standard of Portfolio Management 3rd ed, Section 4.1.3.1, Pg# 46)

- Portfolio Management Plan establishes how a portfolio is defined, organized, optimized, and controlled
- Portfolio Charter is a document that authorizes the portfolio manager to apply portfolio resources to portfolio components. It contains the portfolio structure and determines how the Portfolio will deliver value to the organization.
- Portfolio Roadmap is a document that contain high level chronological graphical depiction of portfolio components, and contains milestones, timelines, deliverables and dependencies. Portfolio Roadmap is a representative of portfolio direction
